HEADWORD: Betony
<hw>Bet"o*ny</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Betonies</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>betony</ets>,
<ets>betany</ets>, F. <ets>betoine</ets>, fr. L. <ets>betonica</ets>,
<ets>vettonica</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A plant of the genus
<gen>Betonica</gen> (Linn.).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The purple or wood betony (<spn>Betonica
officinalis</spn>, Linn.) is common in Europe, being formerly used in
medicine, and (according to Loudon) in dyeing wool a yellow
color.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

